			<td valign="top" class="profile">
				<table cellspacing="4" align="center" width="150">
			
				<tr>
					<td><img src="./styles/subsilver2/imageset/en/icon_user_offline.gif" alt="Offline" title="Offline" /></td>
				</tr>
			
				</table>

				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Mon Sep 27, 2004 2:57 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 835
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Memblers wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I didn't realize why MMC2 and MMC4 use tile $FD and $FE, and not $FF, but after talking with kevtris today I learned the PPU will be doing dummy reads to sprite $FF when there are less than 8 sprites to fetch.</div>
<br />Good call! When I first read Tepples's IRQ idea (and then Tokumaru's follow up), I noticed how similar it was to MMC2/4, and recalled that MMC2/4 used tiles FD and FE (but not FF). That's why I changed the idea to use tile FE when I posted about it; if Nintendo's developers used FD and FE, but not FF, there probably was a good reason. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" />
<br />
<br />But yeah, dummy fetches to tile FF are made because of how the secondary OAM contains dummy data of FFs (save for the first unused byte) when there are less than 8 sprites. I just went to look this up on the wiki so I could add this nugget of info to the PPU rendering section. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" /></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

